3. Core Architecture of ELEMENTS OS

3.1 Five-Layer Architecture

ELEMENTS OS implements a five-layer architecture mirroring the Five Elements:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Layer 5: Human-System Interface (Water)         │
│   • Flowing, adaptive interfaces                │
│   • Qi-based interaction                        │
│   • Pentagram visualization                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Layer 4: Domain-Specific Environments (Metal)   │
│   • Structured, bounded spaces                  │
│   • Value creation environments                 │
│   • Refined domain applications                 │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Layer 3: Elemental Services (Fire)              │
│   • Transformative services                     │
│   • Energy distribution                         │
│   • Process ignition                            │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Layer 2: Wu Xing Kernel - WXK (Earth)           │
│   • Stabilizing core                            │
│   • Balance maintenance                         │
│   • Resource nourishment                        │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ Layer 1: Hardware Abstraction (Wood)            │
│   • Growth-oriented drivers                     │
│   • Expansion capabilities                      │
│   • Planning foundation                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

3.2 The Hardware Abstraction Layer (The Five Organs)

Hardware components are abstracted as TCM (Traditional Chinese Medicine) organs with energetic properties:

· CPU as Liver/Gallbladder (Wood): Planning and execution
· RAM as Heart/Small Intestine (Fire): Consciousness and separation
· Storage as Spleen/Stomach (Earth): Transformation and nourishment
· Network as Lung/Large Intestine (Metal): Boundaries and exchange
· Power Supply as Kidney/Bladder (Water): Foundation and storage

Each "organ" has Qi (energy) flow characteristics, meridian connections to other organs, and self-regulating mechanisms based on TCM principles.

3.3 Wu Xing Kernel (WXK)

The WXK replaces traditional schedulers with cyclical phase scheduling:

```c
// Simplified WXK scheduling algorithm
void wx_schedule() {
    // 1. Calculate current elemental balance
    float balance[5] = calculate_elemental_balance();
    
    // 2. Apply generating cycle nourishment
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        int mother = get_generating_source(i);
        balance[i] += balance[mother] * 0.3; // Mother nourishes child
    }
    
    // 3. Apply controlling cycle regulation  
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        int controller = get_controlling_element(i);
        balance[i] -= balance[controller] * 0.2; // Controller regulates
    }
    
    // 4. Allocate resources proportionally
    allocate_resources_by_balance(balance);
}
```

Processes are classified by elemental characteristics:

· Wood Processes: Planning, compilation, directory traversal
· Fire Processes: Computation, rendering, transformation
· Earth Processes: Storage, database, caching
· Metal Processes: Cleanup, compression, security
· Water Processes: Network, streaming, backup

3.4 Elemental Services Layer

Instead of monolithic services, ELEMENTS OS implements five elemental service types:

1. Wood Services: Growth planning, resource allocation, expansion management
2. Fire Services: Energy transformation, process activation, computation
3. Earth Services: Stability maintenance, resource nourishment, caching
4. Metal Services: Structure refinement, security, cleanup
5. Water Services: Flow management, adaptation, storage

Services interact through meridian connections, following generating and controlling relationships.

3.5 Domain-Specific Environments

Users operate within Domain Spaces—virtual environments optimized for specific activities:

· Health Space: Emphasizes Wood (growth) and Water (rest) elements
· Project Space: Emphasizes Fire (action) and Metal (structure) elements
· Creative Space: Emphasizes Wood (inspiration) and Fire (expression)
· Learning Space: Emphasizes Earth (absorption) and Metal (analysis)
· Financial Space: Emphasizes Metal (value) and Water (flow)

Each space cultivates its elemental balance based on domain needs.

3.6 Human-System Interface (HSI)

Three revolutionary interface paradigms:

1. Taoist CLI: Command-line interface following principles of Wu Wei (non-action) and natural flow
2. Pentagram Visualizer: Real-time visualization of system state as interactive pentagram
3. Qi Flow Interface: Gesture and energy-based interaction using sensors and intention detection

